SIMPLE: flout
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flout
<hw>Flout</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Flouted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Flouting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OD. <ets>fluyten</ets> to play
the flute, to jeer, D. <ets>fluiten</ets>, fr. <ets>fluit</ets>, fr.
French. See <er>Flute</er>.]</ety> <def>To mock or insult; to treat with
contempt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Phillida <qex>flouts</qex> me.</q> <rj><qau>Walton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Three gaudy standards <qex>flout</qex> the pale blue sky.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flout
<hw>Flout</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To practice mocking; to behave
with contempt; to sneer; to fleer; -- often with
<xex>at</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fleer and gibe, and laugh and <qex>flout</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Flout
<hw>Flout</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mock; an insult.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who put your beauty to this <qex>flout</qex> and scorn.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flouter</ent>⟦br⟧
